@R66666666663 @Mudit__Gupta I would seriously doubt that, 4 years is practically an eternity in crypto, how many ICO coins from 4 years ago (2017-2018) still have value today?

@tunasandwich43 The innovation is more on the gauge side I think, the idea of letting people permissionlessly redirect emissions was pretty innovative. CRV > veCRV just takes CRV out of circulation, which burning can do better

@Mudit__Gupta I don't think it makes sense actually. The non-tradeability further pushes lockers to consider the tokens sunk cost, which means they have close to nothing at stake when making decisions affecting the protocol and try to maximize their value extraction instead

@popular_12345 NFT worlds uses NFTs to represent individual servers I think (hence "worlds"), I'm talking about using NFTs to represent land plots in the same server

This has at least two benefits:

- Vote tokens are easily tradeable, so no need for Convex-esque projects on top
- Can use simple staking pool contracts to implement gauges & native bribing, rather than having to fork the complex Curve contracts (written in Vyper no less)

A tokenomics brain worm:

With ve-tokens, tokens locked up for 4 years are usually considered suck cost by lockers. To simplify things, what if you just burnt tokens permanently to get vote tokens, which lets you vote on gauges, get revenue share, etc
You probably have to work with Java though, that's the downside

Free idea for gamefi peeps:

Build a Minecraft server, and sell plots of land as NFTs

Simple, better than cryptovoxels since you have access to Minecraft items & mechanics, better than NFT worlds since land in a popular server is more valuable than worlds with unknown popularity
